{"id":"1807.00361","submitter":"Alexander Kowalski","authors":"Alexander Kowalski, Andreas Hausoel, Markus Wallerberger, Patrik\n  Gunacker, Giorgio Sangiovanni","title":"State- and superstate-sampling in hybridization-expansion\n  continuous-time quantum Monte Carlo","comments":"15 pages, 13 figures; revision of the entire article with many\n  changes in most sections","journal-ref":"Phys. Rev. B 99, 155112 (2019)","doi":"10.1103/PhysRevB.99.155112","report-no":null,"categories":"cond-mat.str-el physics.comp-ph","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  Due to the intrinsic complexity of the quantum many-body problem, quantum\nMonte Carlo algorithms and their corresponding Monte Carlo configurations can\nbe defined in various ways. Configurations corresponding to few Feynman\ndiagrams often lead to severe sign problems. On the other hand, computing the\nconfiguration weight becomes numerically expensive in the opposite limit in\nwhich many diagrams are grouped together. Here we show that for continuous-time\nquantum Monte Carlo in the hybridization expansion the efficiency can be\nsubstantially improved by dividing the local impurity trace into fragments,\nwhich are then sampled individually. For this technique, which also turns out\nto preserve the fermionic sign, a modified update strategy is introduced in\norder to ensure ergodicity. Our (super)state sampling is particularly\nbeneficial to calculations with many $d$-orbitals and general local\ninteractions, such as full Coulomb interaction. For illustration, we reconsider\nthe simple albeit well-known case of a degenerate three-orbital model at low\ntemperatures. This allows us to quantify the coherence properties of the\n\"spin-freezing\" crossover, even close to the Mott transition.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Sun, 1 Jul 2018 17:27:29 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Fri, 3 Aug 2018 06:08:11 GMT"},{"version":"v3","created":"Sat, 27 Apr 2019 14:08:20 GMT"}],"upd